To solve this problem, we can use the concept of directional vectors. We can represent the directions north, south, east, and west as vectors on a plane, and then perform the rotation on these vectors.

Let's represent the direction north as a vector \( \mathbf{n} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \).

Now, we want to rotate this vector by 2250 degrees to the right. A rotation by 2250 degrees can be represented by the matrix

\[
\begin{bmatrix}
\cos(2250) & -\sin(2250) \\
\sin(2250) & \cos(2250)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

We can multiply this matrix by the vector \( \mathbf{n} \) to get the new vector after the rotation.

\[
\mathbf{n'} = \begin{bmatrix}
\cos(2250) & -\sin(2250) \\
\sin(2250) & \cos(2250)
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
0 \\ 1
\end{bmatrix}
\]

Let's calculate \( \mathbf{n'} \).

